(174, 1, '2015-02-25 21:59:40', '2015-02-25 21:59:40', 'You probably know that doing JavaScript testing is good, but one of the hurdles to overcome is how to test our code on different browsers. Luckily, there are some tools available for helping us overcome this hurdle. One of them is a CLI (<em>command line</em>) named <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/saucie" rel="noreferrer"><em>saucie</em></a> developed by <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/igorlima" rel="noreferrer">igorlima</a>. This CLI is a library hosted on <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://www.npmjs.com/" rel="noreferrer">NPM</a>, which allows you to integrate your frontend JavaScript tests with the <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/" rel="noreferrer">SauceLabs</a> platform. SauceLabs makes awesome cross browser testing, and <em>saucie</em> makes it easier to do cross browser testing by CLI.\r\n\r\nA great <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://tobyho.com/2012/06/24/testem-interactive-js-test-runner/" rel="noreferrer">interactive JS Test Runner</a>, the <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/airportyh/testem" rel="noreferrer">testem</a> library, uses <em>saucie</em> on its <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/airportyh/testem/tree/master/examples/saucelabs" rel="noreferrer">examples</a> and has the following <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://jasmine.github.io/" rel="noreferrer">jasmine</a> sample tests:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>hello.js</em></strong>\r\n<div class="highlight highlight-js">\r\n<pre><span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span> <span class="pl-en" style="color: #795da3;">hello</span>(<span class="pl-vpf">name</span>){\r\n    <span class="pl-k" style="color: #a71d5d;">return</span> “hello “ <span class="pl-k" style="color: #a71d5d;">+</span> (name <span class="pl-k" style="color: #a71d5d;">||</span> ‘world’);\r\n}</pre>\r\n</div>\r\n<strong><em>hello_spec.js</em></strong>\r\n<div class="highlight highlight-js">\r\n<pre>describe(‘hello’, <span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span>(){\r\n    it(‘should say hello’, <span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span>(){\r\n        expect(hello()).toBe(‘hello world’);\r\n    });\r\n    it(‘should say hello to person’, <span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span>(){\r\n        expect(hello(‘Bob’)).toBe(‘hello Bob’);\r\n    });\r\n});</pre>\r\n</div>\r\nRun these tests cross platforms step by step - you need only few command lines, as described below:\r\n<ol class="task-list">\r\n	<li>First of all <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/signup/trial" rel="noreferrer">create your SauceLabs account</a></li>\r\n	<li>Make sure the Sauce credentials are set as <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environment_variable" rel="noreferrer">environment variables</a>:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><strong>SAUCE_USERNAME</strong> - your SauceLabs username</li>\r\n	<li><strong>SAUCE_ACCESS_KEY</strong> - your SauceLabs API/Access key.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>After that set up, follow the scripts below:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><code>npm install -g testem saucie</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>git clone git@github.com:airportyh/testem.git</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>cd testem/</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>git checkout tags/v0.7.1</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>cd examples/saucelabs/</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Keep that <strong>first</strong> terminal opened, open a <strong>second</strong> terminal, and follow the script below:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><code>cd testem/examples/saucelabs/</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>testem --port 8080</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Go back to the <strong>first</strong> terminal and type:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><code>saucie --browserNameSL="internet explorer" --versionSL="7.0" --platformSL="Windows XP"</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>saucie --browserNameSL="iphone" --versionSL="8.1" --platformSL="OS X 10.10" --deviceNameSL="iPad Simulator" --deviceOrientationSL="portrait"</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>saucie --browserNameSL="android" --versionSL="4.1" --platformSL="Linux" --deviceNameSL="Motorola Atrix HD Emulator" --deviceOrientationSL="portrait"</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong>Note 1:</strong> <em>All platforms are listed <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/platforms/" rel="noreferrer">here</a>. Want to know the values for browserNameSL, versionSL and platformSL params? Check it <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://docs.saucelabs.com/reference/platforms-configurator/#/" rel="noreferrer">here</a></em>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Note 2:</strong> <em>If you’d like to use the default configuration just type <code>testem ci --port 8080</code> and be happy</em>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Note 3:</strong> <em>type <code>saucie --help</code> to get a help.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Note 4:</strong> <em>testem.yml is a <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/airportyh/testem#configuration-file" rel="noreferrer">configuration file</a> that specifies which JS framework to use. In this case, we are using JasmineJS.</em>\r\n\r\nDo you feel more comfortable watching a <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://showterm.io/592f4be927803a428035e" rel="noreferrer">video</a> instead? Go ahead and watch <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://showterm.io/592f4be927803a428035e" rel="noreferrer">it</a>.\r\n\r\nJust by typing a few command lines, everything was tested on cross browsers. Now let’s go to SauceLabs and check the result on many browsers, including the mobile ones such as iOS and Android:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/tests/06b62f4bba48469999d7212cf1b62818" rel="noreferrer">iOS test video</a></li>\r\n	<li><a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/tests/945ebbe3b6044963a017cef5949d1cf6" rel="noreferrer">IE7 test video</a></li>\r\n	<li><a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/jobs/11bd49cee6cf49d2a76d5b655f6ccb0f" rel="noreferrer">Android test video</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<em>Saucie </em>is still growing up and learning to integrate other platforms like <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://www.browserstack.com/" rel="noreferrer">BrowserStack</a>. New features are coming soon. And these days, it has<a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/igorlima/sauce-js-tests-integration/pull/4" rel="noreferrer"> some improvements</a> from <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/johanneswuerbach" rel="noreferrer">johanneswuerbach</a>. He made several changes <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/johanneswuerbach/ember-cli-sauce/commit/27036f2c97454abb5a2065fb5a754e7c972ddad4" rel="noreferrer">to use <em>saucie</em></a> in <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/johanneswuerbach/ember-cli-sauce" rel="noreferrer">ember-cli-sauce</a>, which is now used by <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/tildeio/htmlbars" rel="noreferrer">htmlbars</a>, the rendering engine used by <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/emberjs/ember.js" rel="noreferrer">emberjs</a>.\r\n\r\nFeel free to file issue and send pull requests and let’s become <em>saucie</em> even better. Thanks!', 'Getting started with Saucie CLI', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'getting-started-with-saucie-cli', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:12:52', '2015-05-18 17:12:52', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=174', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(175, 1, '2015-02-18 21:58:03', '2015-02-18 21:58:03', '<h2><b>Key Facts</b></h2>\r\n<b>Locations: </b>Corporate HQ in Pittsburgh, PA, and retail stores worldwide\r\n\r\n<b>Industry: </b>Retail - Youth Apparel\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The Word </b><b> </b></h2>\r\n<b>From the Project Manager to our UI Developer </b>\r\n<blockquote>I had been fighting for these changes for five months! It was our biggest pain point for our call centers...every day they complain about it. You have saved the day!</blockquote>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The challenge</b></h2>\r\nWhat can be done without an experienced UI team? Not much of anything, really. But Our client needed UI improvements that supported their plans for global expansion, and they had their eyes on the UK and needed their website to truly represent them as a company. The last code written for the website dated back to 2008, with most of it written years before. We stepped in to give them the UI guidance they needed to take their website to the next level. In order for the UI to support their expansion plans, there were serious updates needed to be done for the CSR Application too:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Currency conversion for international business</li>\r\n	<li>Complete website redesign</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The Journey</b></h2>\r\n<b>Currency conversion for international business</b>\r\n\r\nOur client’s internal e-commerce system only supported currency conversions that either went to or from US dollars. So for those ordering from the UK but using Euros, there was no hope other than to use 3rd party online tools. We designed a module that had the intelligence to call internal API’s to convert the foreign currencies to other foreign currencies without the customer have to worry about using US dollars. This CSR app supports anywhere between 300 or 400 customer representatives at a time, so it needed to be nimble. This module created the workaround by using AJAX, which detected which currency the user was coming from and going to simply by pinging the server, and then created a new, appropriate currency conversion rate based on the information it found on the web.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Complete website redesign</b>\r\n\r\nThere hadn’t been any new UI enhancements added to the website since 2008...and it was obvious. The site needed a serious facelift. It was created in a time when adaptive/responsive design frameworks didn’t exist and IE7 was considered cutting edge - yikes! We dusted the cobwebs off the code, and set to work. For starters, we created a login screen that used modern AJAX &amp; CSS3 for the login screen which communicated errors via animations. Then we created a bulletin board which allowed messages to be left for employees which kept them up to date on news. We integrated social media as well, which helped customer service reps know what was going on in real time, catch any issues before they bubbled over, and gave them insight which created a true sense of empathy. This improved their customer support success and customers were overjoyed.', 'Fortune 1000 Retailer', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'fortune-1000-retailer', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:13:02', '2015-05-18 17:13:02', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=175', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(176, 1, '2015-02-18 21:57:26', '2015-02-18 21:57:26', '<h2>Brazilian beginnings</h2>\r\nI decided to come to the US after working for three years as a consultant after knowing  that I was unhappy with what I was currently doing, and living in a city where you can''t go anywhere without feeling unsafe. The last straw was being mugged while stuck in traffic going home after work.\r\nThat same month I applied for the Toefl Exam (needed for pretty much any school here in the US), and started looking for a program that wouldn''t be too hard to get in and would also add to my resume. One of my co-workers told me about the UC Berkeley Extension course and it sounded like a good option. I did a little bit more research, and decided to take the Project Management Certification Course since it was related to my bachelor’s degree in business, and also added to my work history as a business consultant. After that decision, I had to decide between IDP (International diploma) or ECP (Evening Certificate Program). The main difference is that one is only for international students, and the second one is mainly for people that have a full-time job already, but still want to invest in their education. I disliked the idea of taking a course with people that were only there to study, because I wanted to be around Americans that actually worked,  since it would help me get a real glimpse of what it would be like if I was to live in America. I enjoyed the whole course and made a lot of connections, but when the end of my program was approaching and I was starting to look for an intern position, I realized how hard it was to be from another country while getting companies to give me a chance.\r\n<h2>A foot in the door</h2>\r\nAfter talking to all my teachers, one of them (Introduction to Agile) put me in contact with Amir, but that didn''t work the first time (he was traveling and we stopped exchanging emails after a while). I emailed that teacher again, and this time she put me in contact with Zeo and we scheduled a meeting. I went to the Avenue Code office, and Zeo was pretty straightforward with me. He told me that at that point I couldn''t add any value, but he could put me in contact with Elaine, as she was developing a new project that I would be a good fit for. I had no idea about the whole Cadet Program concept, and met with Elaine without knowing what to expect. I went to one of the client sites to talk to her, and she explained that I could be a unpaid intern and participate in the Code Academy project as a Cadet. I was happy with the opportunity, but I didn''t know how I would tell my parents (who had been sponsoring me while I went to UC Berkeley) that I would like to stay one more year in America without any paycheck. After some discussion and a lot of thinking, I felt that it was a great opportunity and even though my parents said they would not sponsor me anymore, I decided to use my personal savings and invest in myself. Shortly after that, I finished my extension, and went back to Brazil to spend some time with my family and renew my visa.\r\n<h2>On the right track</h2>\r\nI got to Avenue Code by the end of August, and stayed with Avenue Code for the first fifteen days. That was a huge help! During those two weeks, I was going crazy trying to find a place to live. The first day at Avenue Code, Elaine took me to lunch and we chatted a little bit more about what she had planned for me. Since the beginning, she was really open to my suggestions. I believed I should just go with the flow, and eventually it would all make sense. She set two meetings with two different companies, and we agreed that I would work two days in one as a project manager intern, and three days in the other as a scrum master intern. I had no idea what I was going to do in either positions, and I was freaking out about not being able to do a great job, but Elaine always told me to be patient and just be a sponge. The first internship  didn''t work out that well. They were going through some issues with their vendor and also rearranging  their team so I couldn''t help much and felt like I always had to find things to do. The project was so bad that they were considering finding another vendor.\r\n\r\nThe second internship was completely different! I loved it from day one, and my mentor there, Elle, helped me since the beginning and always made sure I was learning something new. Since I do not have a tech background, it was tough finding the rhythm during the first three to four weeks but eventually got easier. Elaine touched base with me every two to four weeks but she did not interfere much in this first “stage”.\r\n<h2>Gaining momentum</h2>\r\nMid-November I started interviewing with a Fortune 100 Retail company and after two brief interviews, (with no prep - Elaine wanted me to be myself and didn''t provide any info!) Elaine told me I would be starting with them right away! I wanted to finalize my internship with my previous internship so I asked if I could work in both for one to two weeks. I also did that because my mentor at my previous internship was out of the office during that period and I was in charge. I owe a lot to her because she trusted me enough to be in charge during her absence.\r\n\r\nOnce I started at my new internship, everything changed! Here Elaine had given me amazing support and always wanted me to provide feedback and prep for my first meetings (coaching me with “fake meetings”).\r\n<h2>Like an internship, but better</h2>\r\nI was on-boarding for six weeks and started as an Iteration Manager. In the beginning, I was not confident and afraid I was not ready, but my mentor was always there to support me and remind me that they knew I was junior and an intern. I have just completed a month now and even though I know I’ve got a lot to learn I feel more confident. The support I''ve been getting from Avenue Code, and especially my mentor, still surprises me. I am not used to the concept of people investing in me simply because they believe in me. That is something I really love about Avenue Code, and my goal is to give back by being a great resource by help us win new clients and keeping the relationship strong with current ones.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Agile Cadet Program: A Firsthand Account', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'agile-cadet-program-a-firsthand-account', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:13:15', '2015-05-18 17:13:15', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=176', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(177, 1, '2015-05-12 19:43:17', '2015-05-12 19:43:17', '<h2><b>Key Facts</b></h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Locations: </b>Corporate HQ in Pittsburgh, PA, and retail stores worldwide.\r\n\r\n<b>Industry: </b>Retail - Youth Apparel\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The Word </b><b> </b></h2>\r\nFrom the Project Manager to our UI Developer\r\n<blockquote>I had been fighting for these changes for five months! It was our biggest pain point for our call centers...every day they complain about it. You have saved the day!</blockquote>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The challenge</b></h2>\r\nWhat can be done without an experienced UI team? Not much of anything, really. But our client needed UI improvements that supported their plans for global expansion, and  they had their eyes on the UK and needed their website to truly represent them as a company. The last code written for the website dated back to 2008, with most of it written years before. We stepped in to give them the UI guidance they needed to take their website to the next level. In order for the UI to support their expansion plans, there were serious updates needed to be done for the CSR Application too:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Currency conversion for international business</li>\r\n	<li>Complete website redesign</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The Journey</b></h2>\r\n<b>Currency conversion for international business</b>\r\n\r\nOur client''s internal e-commerce system only supported currency conversions that either went to or from US dollars. So for those ordering from the UK but using Euros, there was no hope other than to use 3rd party online tools. We designed a module that had the intelligence to call internal API’s to convert the foreign currencies to other foreign currencies without the customer have to worry about using US dollars. This CSR app supports anywhere between 300 or 400 customer representatives at a time, so it needed to be nimble. This module created the workaround by using AJAX, which detected which currency the user was coming from and going to simply by pinging the server, and then created a new, appropriate currency conversion rate based on the information it found on the web.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Complete website redesign</b>\r\n\r\nThere hadn’t been any new UI enhancements added to the website since 2008...and it was obvious. The site needed a serious facelift. It was created in a time when adaptive/responsive design frameworks didn’t exist and IE7 was considered cutting edge - yikes! We dusted the cobwebs off the code, and set to work. For starters, we created a login screen that used modern AJAX &amp; CSS3 for the login screen which communicated errors via animations. Then we created a bulletin board which allowed messages to be left for employees which kept them up to date on news. We integrated social media as well, which helped customer service reps know what was going on in real time, catch any issues before they bubbled over, and gave them insight which created a true sense of empathy. This improved their customer support success and customers were overjoyed.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>Results</b></h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><b>                                                    </b></p>', 'American Eagle Outfitters', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'american-eagle-outfitters', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:43:39', '2015-05-12 19:43:39', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=177', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(178, 1, '2015-05-12 19:41:34', '2015-05-12 19:41:34', '', 'Getting-startedwith-saucie-Cli', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'getting-startedwith-saucie-cli', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:41:34', '2015-05-12 19:41:34', '', 174, 'http://localhost/acnew/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Getting-startedwith-saucie-Cli.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(179, 1, '2015-05-12 19:41:40', '2015-05-12 19:41:40', 'You probably know that doing JavaScript testing is good, but one of the hurdles to overcome is how to test our code on different browsers. Luckily, there are some tools available for helping us overcome this hurdle. One of them is a CLI (<em>command line</em>) named <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/saucie" rel="noreferrer"><em>saucie</em></a> developed by <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/igorlima" rel="noreferrer">igorlima</a>. This CLI is a library hosted on <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://www.npmjs.com/" rel="noreferrer">NPM</a>, which allows you to integrate your frontend JavaScript tests with the <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/" rel="noreferrer">SauceLabs</a> platform. SauceLabs makes awesome cross browser testing, and <em>saucie</em> makes it easier to do cross browser testing by CLI.\r\n\r\nA great <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://tobyho.com/2012/06/24/testem-interactive-js-test-runner/" rel="noreferrer">interactive JS Test Runner</a>, the <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/airportyh/testem" rel="noreferrer">testem</a> library, uses <em>saucie</em> on its <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/airportyh/testem/tree/master/examples/saucelabs" rel="noreferrer">examples</a> and has the following <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://jasmine.github.io/" rel="noreferrer">jasmine</a> sample tests:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>hello.js</em></strong>\r\n<div class="highlight highlight-js">\r\n<pre><span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span> <span class="pl-en" style="color: #795da3;">hello</span>(<span class="pl-vpf">name</span>){\r\n    <span class="pl-k" style="color: #a71d5d;">return</span> “hello “ <span class="pl-k" style="color: #a71d5d;">+</span> (name <span class="pl-k" style="color: #a71d5d;">||</span> ‘world’);\r\n}</pre>\r\n</div>\r\n<strong><em>hello_spec.js</em></strong>\r\n<div class="highlight highlight-js">\r\n<pre>describe(‘hello’, <span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span>(){\r\n    it(‘should say hello’, <span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span>(){\r\n        expect(hello()).toBe(‘hello world’);\r\n    });\r\n    it(‘should say hello to person’, <span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span>(){\r\n        expect(hello(‘Bob’)).toBe(‘hello Bob’);\r\n    });\r\n});</pre>\r\n</div>\r\nRun these tests cross platforms step by step - you need only few command lines, as described below:\r\n<ol class="task-list">\r\n	<li>First of all <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/signup/trial" rel="noreferrer">create your SauceLabs account</a></li>\r\n	<li>Make sure the Sauce credentials are set as <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environment_variable" rel="noreferrer">environment variables</a>:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><strong>SAUCE_USERNAME</strong> - your SauceLabs username</li>\r\n	<li><strong>SAUCE_ACCESS_KEY</strong> - your SauceLabs API/Access key.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>After that set up, follow the scripts below:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><code>npm install -g testem saucie</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>git clone git@github.com:airportyh/testem.git</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>cd testem/</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>git checkout tags/v0.7.1</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>cd examples/saucelabs/</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Keep that <strong>first</strong> terminal opened, open a <strong>second</strong> terminal, and follow the script below:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><code>cd testem/examples/saucelabs/</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>testem --port 8080</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Go back to the <strong>first</strong> terminal and type:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><code>saucie --browserNameSL="internet explorer" --versionSL="7.0" --platformSL="Windows XP"</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>saucie --browserNameSL="iphone" --versionSL="8.1" --platformSL="OS X 10.10" --deviceNameSL="iPad Simulator" --deviceOrientationSL="portrait"</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>saucie --browserNameSL="android" --versionSL="4.1" --platformSL="Linux" --deviceNameSL="Motorola Atrix HD Emulator" --deviceOrientationSL="portrait"</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong>Note 1:</strong> <em>All platforms are listed <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/platforms/" rel="noreferrer">here</a>. Want to know the values for browserNameSL, versionSL and platformSL params? Check it <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://docs.saucelabs.com/reference/platforms-configurator/#/" rel="noreferrer">here</a></em>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Note 2:</strong> <em>If you’d like to use the default configuration just type <code>testem ci --port 8080</code> and be happy</em>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Note 3:</strong> <em>type <code>saucie --help</code> to get a help.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Note 4:</strong> <em>testem.yml is a <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/airportyh/testem#configuration-file" rel="noreferrer">configuration file</a> that specifies which JS framework to use. In this case, we are using JasmineJS.</em>\r\n\r\nDo you feel more comfortable watching a <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://showterm.io/592f4be927803a428035e" rel="noreferrer">video</a> instead? Go ahead and watch <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://showterm.io/592f4be927803a428035e" rel="noreferrer">it</a>.\r\n\r\nJust by typing a few command lines, everything was tested on cross browsers. Now let’s go to SauceLabs and check the result on many browsers, including the mobile ones such as iOS and Android:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/tests/06b62f4bba48469999d7212cf1b62818" rel="noreferrer">iOS test video</a></li>\r\n	<li><a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/tests/945ebbe3b6044963a017cef5949d1cf6" rel="noreferrer">IE7 test video</a></li>\r\n	<li><a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/jobs/11bd49cee6cf49d2a76d5b655f6ccb0f" rel="noreferrer">Android test video</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<em>Saucie </em>is still growing up and learning to integrate other platforms like <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://www.browserstack.com/" rel="noreferrer">BrowserStack</a>. New features are coming soon. And these days, it has<a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/igorlima/sauce-js-tests-integration/pull/4" rel="noreferrer"> some improvements</a> from <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/johanneswuerbach" rel="noreferrer">johanneswuerbach</a>. He made several changes <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/johanneswuerbach/ember-cli-sauce/commit/27036f2c97454abb5a2065fb5a754e7c972ddad4" rel="noreferrer">to use <em>saucie</em></a> in <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/johanneswuerbach/ember-cli-sauce" rel="noreferrer">ember-cli-sauce</a>, which is now used by <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/tildeio/htmlbars" rel="noreferrer">htmlbars</a>, the rendering engine used by <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/emberjs/ember.js" rel="noreferrer">emberjs</a>.\r\n\r\nFeel free to file issue and send pull requests and let’s become <em>saucie</em> even better. Thanks!', 'Getting started with Saucie CLI', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '174-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:41:40', '2015-05-12 19:41:40', '', 174, 'http://localhost/acnew/174-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(180, 1, '2015-05-12 19:41:59', '2015-05-12 19:41:59', '', 'AE', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'ae', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:41:59', '2015-05-12 19:41:59', '', 175, 'http://localhost/acnew/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/AE.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(181, 1, '2015-05-12 19:42:03', '2015-05-12 19:42:03', '<h2><b>Key Facts</b></h2>\r\n<b>Locations: </b>Corporate HQ in Pittsburgh, PA, and retail stores worldwide\r\n\r\n<b>Industry: </b>Retail - Youth Apparel\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The Word </b><b> </b></h2>\r\n<b>From the Project Manager to our UI Developer </b>\r\n<blockquote>I had been fighting for these changes for five months! It was our biggest pain point for our call centers...every day they complain about it. You have saved the day!</blockquote>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The challenge</b></h2>\r\nWhat can be done without an experienced UI team? Not much of anything, really. But Our client needed UI improvements that supported their plans for global expansion, and they had their eyes on the UK and needed their website to truly represent them as a company. The last code written for the website dated back to 2008, with most of it written years before. We stepped in to give them the UI guidance they needed to take their website to the next level. In order for the UI to support their expansion plans, there were serious updates needed to be done for the CSR Application too:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Currency conversion for international business</li>\r\n	<li>Complete website redesign</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The Journey</b></h2>\r\n<b>Currency conversion for international business</b>\r\n\r\nOur client’s internal e-commerce system only supported currency conversions that either went to or from US dollars. So for those ordering from the UK but using Euros, there was no hope other than to use 3rd party online tools. We designed a module that had the intelligence to call internal API’s to convert the foreign currencies to other foreign currencies without the customer have to worry about using US dollars. This CSR app supports anywhere between 300 or 400 customer representatives at a time, so it needed to be nimble. This module created the workaround by using AJAX, which detected which currency the user was coming from and going to simply by pinging the server, and then created a new, appropriate currency conversion rate based on the information it found on the web.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Complete website redesign</b>\r\n\r\nThere hadn’t been any new UI enhancements added to the website since 2008...and it was obvious. The site needed a serious facelift. It was created in a time when adaptive/responsive design frameworks didn’t exist and IE7 was considered cutting edge - yikes! We dusted the cobwebs off the code, and set to work. For starters, we created a login screen that used modern AJAX &amp; CSS3 for the login screen which communicated errors via animations. Then we created a bulletin board which allowed messages to be left for employees which kept them up to date on news. We integrated social media as well, which helped customer service reps know what was going on in real time, catch any issues before they bubbled over, and gave them insight which created a true sense of empathy. This improved their customer support success and customers were overjoyed.', 'Fortune 1000 Retailer', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '175-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:42:03', '2015-05-12 19:42:03', '', 175, 'http://localhost/acnew/175-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(182, 1, '2015-05-12 19:42:20', '2015-05-12 19:42:20', '', 'Cadet-program-2', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'cadet-program-2', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:42:20', '2015-05-12 19:42:20', '', 176, 'http://localhost/acnew/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Cadet-program-2.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(183, 1, '2015-05-12 19:42:26', '2015-05-12 19:42:26', '<h2>Brazilian beginnings</h2>\r\nI decided to come to the US after working for three years as a consultant after knowing  that I was unhappy with what I was currently doing, and living in a city where you can''t go anywhere without feeling unsafe. The last straw was being mugged while stuck in traffic going home after work.\r\nThat same month I applied for the Toefl Exam (needed for pretty much any school here in the US), and started looking for a program that wouldn''t be too hard to get in and would also add to my resume. One of my co-workers told me about the UC Berkeley Extension course and it sounded like a good option. I did a little bit more research, and decided to take the Project Management Certification Course since it was related to my bachelor’s degree in business, and also added to my work history as a business consultant. After that decision, I had to decide between IDP (International diploma) or ECP (Evening Certificate Program). The main difference is that one is only for international students, and the second one is mainly for people that have a full-time job already, but still want to invest in their education. I disliked the idea of taking a course with people that were only there to study, because I wanted to be around Americans that actually worked,  since it would help me get a real glimpse of what it would be like if I was to live in America. I enjoyed the whole course and made a lot of connections, but when the end of my program was approaching and I was starting to look for an intern position, I realized how hard it was to be from another country while getting companies to give me a chance.\r\n<h2>A foot in the door</h2>\r\nAfter talking to all my teachers, one of them (Introduction to Agile) put me in contact with Amir, but that didn''t work the first time (he was traveling and we stopped exchanging emails after a while). I emailed that teacher again, and this time she put me in contact with Zeo and we scheduled a meeting. I went to the Avenue Code office, and Zeo was pretty straightforward with me. He told me that at that point I couldn''t add any value, but he could put me in contact with Elaine, as she was developing a new project that I would be a good fit for. I had no idea about the whole Cadet Program concept, and met with Elaine without knowing what to expect. I went to one of the client sites to talk to her, and she explained that I could be a unpaid intern and participate in the Code Academy project as a Cadet. I was happy with the opportunity, but I didn''t know how I would tell my parents (who had been sponsoring me while I went to UC Berkeley) that I would like to stay one more year in America without any paycheck. After some discussion and a lot of thinking, I felt that it was a great opportunity and even though my parents said they would not sponsor me anymore, I decided to use my personal savings and invest in myself. Shortly after that, I finished my extension, and went back to Brazil to spend some time with my family and renew my visa.\r\n<h2>On the right track</h2>\r\nI got to Avenue Code by the end of August, and stayed with Avenue Code for the first fifteen days. That was a huge help! During those two weeks, I was going crazy trying to find a place to live. The first day at Avenue Code, Elaine took me to lunch and we chatted a little bit more about what she had planned for me. Since the beginning, she was really open to my suggestions. I believed I should just go with the flow, and eventually it would all make sense. She set two meetings with two different companies, and we agreed that I would work two days in one as a project manager intern, and three days in the other as a scrum master intern. I had no idea what I was going to do in either positions, and I was freaking out about not being able to do a great job, but Elaine always told me to be patient and just be a sponge. The first internship  didn''t work out that well. They were going through some issues with their vendor and also rearranging  their team so I couldn''t help much and felt like I always had to find things to do. The project was so bad that they were considering finding another vendor.\r\n\r\nThe second internship was completely different! I loved it from day one, and my mentor there, Elle, helped me since the beginning and always made sure I was learning something new. Since I do not have a tech background, it was tough finding the rhythm during the first three to four weeks but eventually got easier. Elaine touched base with me every two to four weeks but she did not interfere much in this first “stage”.\r\n<h2>Gaining momentum</h2>\r\nMid-November I started interviewing with a Fortune 100 Retail company and after two brief interviews, (with no prep - Elaine wanted me to be myself and didn''t provide any info!) Elaine told me I would be starting with them right away! I wanted to finalize my internship with my previous internship so I asked if I could work in both for one to two weeks. I also did that because my mentor at my previous internship was out of the office during that period and I was in charge. I owe a lot to her because she trusted me enough to be in charge during her absence.\r\n\r\nOnce I started at my new internship, everything changed! Here Elaine had given me amazing support and always wanted me to provide feedback and prep for my first meetings (coaching me with “fake meetings”).\r\n<h2>Like an internship, but better</h2>\r\nI was on-boarding for six weeks and started as an Iteration Manager. In the beginning, I was not confident and afraid I was not ready, but my mentor was always there to support me and remind me that they knew I was junior and an intern. I have just completed a month now and even though I know I’ve got a lot to learn I feel more confident. The support I''ve been getting from Avenue Code, and especially my mentor, still surprises me. I am not used to the concept of people investing in me simply because they believe in me. That is something I really love about Avenue Code, and my goal is to give back by being a great resource by help us win new clients and keeping the relationship strong with current ones.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Agile Cadet Program: A Firsthand Account', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '176-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:42:26', '2015-05-12 19:42:26', '', 176, 'http://localhost/acnew/176-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(184, 1, '2015-05-12 19:43:17', '2015-05-12 19:43:17', '<h2><b>Key Facts</b></h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Locations: </b>Corporate HQ in Pittsburgh, PA, and retail stores worldwide.\r\n\r\n<b>Industry: </b>Retail - Youth Apparel\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The Word </b><b> </b></h2>\r\nFrom the Project Manager to our UI Developer\r\n<blockquote>I had been fighting for these changes for five months! It was our biggest pain point for our call centers...every day they complain about it. You have saved the day!</blockquote>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The challenge</b></h2>\r\nWhat can be done without an experienced UI team? Not much of anything, really. But our client needed UI improvements that supported their plans for global expansion, and  they had their eyes on the UK and needed their website to truly represent them as a company. The last code written for the website dated back to 2008, with most of it written years before. We stepped in to give them the UI guidance they needed to take their website to the next level. In order for the UI to support their expansion plans, there were serious updates needed to be done for the CSR Application too:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Currency conversion for international business</li>\r\n	<li>Complete website redesign</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The Journey</b></h2>\r\n<b>Currency conversion for international business</b>\r\n\r\nOur client''s internal e-commerce system only supported currency conversions that either went to or from US dollars. So for those ordering from the UK but using Euros, there was no hope other than to use 3rd party online tools. We designed a module that had the intelligence to call internal API’s to convert the foreign currencies to other foreign currencies without the customer have to worry about using US dollars. This CSR app supports anywhere between 300 or 400 customer representatives at a time, so it needed to be nimble. This module created the workaround by using AJAX, which detected which currency the user was coming from and going to simply by pinging the server, and then created a new, appropriate currency conversion rate based on the information it found on the web.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Complete website redesign</b>\r\n\r\nThere hadn’t been any new UI enhancements added to the website since 2008...and it was obvious. The site needed a serious facelift. It was created in a time when adaptive/responsive design frameworks didn’t exist and IE7 was considered cutting edge - yikes! We dusted the cobwebs off the code, and set to work. For starters, we created a login screen that used modern AJAX &amp; CSS3 for the login screen which communicated errors via animations. Then we created a bulletin board which allowed messages to be left for employees which kept them up to date on news. We integrated social media as well, which helped customer service reps know what was going on in real time, catch any issues before they bubbled over, and gave them insight which created a true sense of empathy. This improved their customer support success and customers were overjoyed.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>Results</b></h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><b>                                                    </b></p>', 'American Eagle Outfitters', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '177-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:43:17', '2015-05-12 19:43:17', '', 177, 'http://localhost/acnew/177-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(185, 1, '2015-01-30 21:56:23', '2015-01-30 21:56:23', '<h2>If you don''t use it, you lose it</h2>\r\nWe all know that becoming a solid software developer is not something that happens in a day.\r\n\r\nHowever, one should not stop learning when he knows enough coding to land a good job. Coding is an exercise like running, swimming, or playing a musical instrument: if you don''t practice enough, you will get rusty.\r\n\r\nIt''s worth noting there are several categories of coding problems which we do not usually exercise in our everyday jobs, like algorithms to deal with sorting, searching, compressing, cryptography, artificial intelligence, machine learning, combinatorics, or geometry...\r\n\r\nNot only that, but as time goes by, other paradigms come forth in order to solve problems in a faster and more clever way, like Functional Programming and Reactive Programming.\r\n<h2>Leveling up</h2>\r\nThat said, there is just one way to keep sharp on software development: <strong>practicing</strong>. Now tell me: do you revel in leveling up while playing videogames, solving a Rubik''s cube, or even doing crosswords?\r\n\r\nSo why not taking coding challenges as well?\r\n\r\nI believe that every self-respecting software developer should put aside some weekly time to solve coding challenges. I personally strive for doing at least one short challenge per day. Over time, it starts to get entertaining, fun, and even addictive!\r\n\r\nThere are quite a few good websites that can provide great coding challenges to play with, leveling from 101 to top-notch. The beauty of it is that you will learn a lot when you compare your solution with others from the community. I believe that this way I will turn out to be a better developer on the long run. Besides, they end up being great puzzles to play with!\r\n<h2></h2>\r\nThese are short code challenge websites:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.codewars.com/">http://www.codewars.com/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.hackerrank.com/">http://www.hackerrank.com/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.hackerearth.com/">http://www.hackerearth.com/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf you would rather taking longer and more complex challenges (and sometimes get prizes for it):\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.topcoder.com/">http://www.topcoder.com/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://code.google.com/codejam">https://code.google.com/codejam</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.codechef.com/">http://www.codechef.com/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAnd if you only want to have fun, there are real videogames that you have to code in order to progress:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://codecombat.com/">http://codecombat.com/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.kuatostudios.com/games/hakitzu-elite/">http://www.kuatostudios.com/games/hakitzu-elite/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://play.elevatorsaga.com/">http://play.elevatorsaga.com/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nGive them a try and rejoice!', 'Enlighten your coding skills as you would play a videogame', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'enlighten-your-coding-skills-as-you-would-play-a-videogame', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:13:26', '2015-05-18 17:13:26', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=185', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(186, 1, '2015-01-29 21:55:44', '2015-01-29 21:55:44', '<h2>The beginning</h2>\r\nThere I was. 24 years old, just got out of the University with my bachelor''s degree in Information Systems. Time to march out to face the competition and make a name for myself in the world. Some doors were opened but they would not lead far. I had to do something that would be worth my time and take advantage of everything I learned. But colleges nowadays are so far removed from what companies actually need! Even though they know how to teach people to think and make the best out of themselves.\r\n<h2>First steps</h2>\r\nSo what’s almost more valuable than your degree? Connections. A friend that was an Avenue Code Insider told me about a job opening, as I was working in mobile development at the time. "Send me your skills by email in English", he said. Some time passed by, and then I found myself at the Belo Horizonte''s office doing the interview. "Do you speak English?" they asked. I was confident about it, but, despite my language skills, I knew I was about to deal with my first interview totally in English. The lack of practice did not diminish my thinking skills, and, in the end, I was being seen as a potential developer. "You got skills, but you still don''t have the requirements we would like you to have. For these people, we offer the Trainee Program."\r\n<h2>Proving ground</h2>\r\nYes, I got in. And I would have three months to prove my value as a fast learner and competent developer. I aimed to improve every UI skill: HTML, CSS, Javascript, version control, modern frameworks, best practices, everything one may find as a trending topic in front-end conferences. I talked to people about where should I start, went to online teaching websites, found instructive videos, and made myself aware.\r\n\r\nSocially, Avenue Code''s flat hierarchy helped by giving me more space to ask questions, but the major difference was really the employees’ proactive way of helping, despite their deadlines and projects. On the other hand, the freedom of learning at my own pace, and not knowing where to apply that, put me in a gray area.\r\n<h2>Getting my hands dirty</h2>\r\nIn the mean time, I was put on an internal project. It helped me build chemistry with my co-workers and also build my knowledge. It was an awesome experience for me, as I could focus on putting my recent learnings into practice. Also, I could see how a project worked from the inside and contribute to challenges I could come across only in theory while at the university.\r\n\r\nAs part of the Trainee process, I had to pick one topic and do a talk. I chose Ember.js and the talk is <a href="http://youtu.be/mmMxaCRz9Mg">here</a>. It was a major achievement for me: it was great to see all the people attending my talk because I had something new to share, despite being a newcomer. After three months of dedication, I was hired. I am currently working on a client and I feel that I''ve been completely integrated into the Avenue Code team. There is much to be achieved and I appreciate the opportunity to grow as a UI Developer.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'From Trainee to UI Developer', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'from-trainee-to-ui-developer', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:13:34', '2015-05-18 17:13:34', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=186', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(187, 1, '2015-01-23 21:54:09', '2015-01-23 21:54:09', '<h1>Key Facts</h1>\r\n<b>Locations: </b>America HQ – Stores Worldwide\r\n\r\n<b>Industry: </b>Retail\r\n\r\n<b># engineers supported: </b>1,000\r\n<h2><b>The Word</b></h2>\r\n<blockquote>We reached our ROI before the Agile transformation was even completed. Avenue Code executed where others had failed.</blockquote>\r\n- SVP\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The Challenge</b></h2>\r\nThe management of smaller companies is a normal part of growth, but ensuring they all mature at the same rate can be extremely complicated. Getting all the companies which operate under one parent company speaking the same language comes with much frustration. Our client had this exact issue when we first met them. There was a handful of challenges that arose from this “synchronous maturity” problem. Let’s start from the top:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>General Parity Issues</b>\r\n\r\nThe parent company had a web division [Company A] with an engineering team, but the sister company [Company B] did not. However, these two subsidiaries operated independently of one another, which meant that developing new software to be used by both was too expensive. First, Company A would have to create it, then Company B would try to replicate it with their own IT organization or have to flat out buy it. This software duplication kept the client from progressing technologically. In Company B, IT was essentially non-existent, which made even insignificant changes a headache. In Company A, they had both software development and a website to manage, but no synchronous strategy with their lagging sister company. What they desperately needed was a team of agile experts to transform their organizations into one unified effort.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Financial Remodeling</b>\r\n\r\nResources were unevenly spent due to their original financial model. Before Avenue Code stepped in, engineers were only given financial incentives based on Company A’s website revenue, which left Company B neglected.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Product Development Parity Issues </b>\r\n\r\nMuch like the general parity issue, the product and project managers were only provided for Company A and not Company B. Naturally, they focused all their efforts on just Company A, instead of both of the subsidiaries. Company B was left having to buy the technology they needed, instead of being able to use it jointly.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Absence of an IT Org</b>\r\n\r\nSince only Company A had an IT organization, the technology was only updated and created for that company. This left Company B’s software innovation in the dust.\r\n\r\n<b>The Solution</b>\r\n\r\nSolving the parity problem set off a domino effect between the two subsidiaries. We started with a strategic infrastructure plan. In this plan we created an engineering team for the Company B, which was being neglected by the limited IT structure at the sister company. Now there wouldn’t be the strain of two companies on a team meant to meet the needs of just one company. Similarly, we also designed the developer financial incentives to reflect the success of both the subsidiaries’ website performance combined.\r\n\r\nTo ensure that product development ran smoothly for both companies, we nominated the proper amount of product and project managers for each. After this was accomplished, we unified the software development tools. These tools, paired with their respective program management teams, allowed for quicker software development for both companies.\r\n\r\nWhen companies are a part of a larger organization, it can be a headache to get them operating at the same speed. Luckily, we were able to find the pain points in these subsidiaries and fix them so that each company had the proper team to support the overall needs of the client. The results were incredible. Never underestimate the power of a proper strategic infrastructure plan.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>Results</b></h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Client’s overall IT costs were decreased by $40 million</li>\r\n	<li>Project delivery increased by 300%</li>\r\n	<li>Company B saved 60% of IT costs</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Fortune 100 Retailer', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'fortune-100-retailer', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:13:43', '2015-05-18 17:13:43', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=187', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(188, 1, '2015-01-21 21:53:35', '2015-01-21 21:53:35', 'Avenue Code recently invited some Chef gurus to our office to outline the state of devops and the benefits of continuous delivery for our Avenue Code family. Here are some of the insights we got from the Lunch n'' Learn!\r\n<h2>Got data?</h2>\r\nEveryone is becoming a software company (even if they fight it). Whether they are web innovators or enterprise giants, they collectively need to move vast quantities of data from data centers to the cloud. Such large amounts of data require a top notch software team to handle frequent iterations of code. This team can only function with a continuous delivery platform on hand.\r\n\r\nWe know that our customers are companies with an exceptionally high demand for continuous delivery.  Specifically, those with a strong web presence and significant e-commerce business, as they have a need to manipulate and analyze large quantities of data. These companies depend on rapid iterations to process data in real-time. Such a high velocity of software development is only made short, quick, and successful if there are the proper devops in place to support it. Chef provides the automation and delivery platform to build, deploy, and manage the code needed for the continuous delivery these companies seek.\r\n<h2>Chef for all</h2>\r\nGenerally, it is extremely hard for large IT organizations to become a software-based company, but with Chef, they have the automation to do so. However, every company has varied code and thus, different needs. That’s where we come in. After Chef has been installed, Avenue Code provides the bridge between the platform and the specialized integration needs of the customer. We are the consultants that help their teams adopt Chef properly.\r\nSince Chef is open source, many companies are hoping to create their own products based on the code. However, most of these companies do not have the Chef skill set to create such products. Luckily, we can also help there as well. Not only will we be implementing their offerings with our current clients, but we have added them to our lineup for Avenue Code Academy! This means anyone can learn how to harness the power of Chef. Our next Chef Fundamentals class is going to be February 3rd and 4th! Save your seat today<a href="http://ow.ly/HIpEu%20" target="_blank"> by following this link.</a>', 'Chef Lunch n'' learn', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'chef-lunch-n-learn', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:13:54', '2015-05-18 17:13:54', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=188', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(189, 1, '2015-05-12 19:46:21', '2015-05-12 19:46:21', '', 'Enlighten-your-coding-skills-as-you-2', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'enlighten-your-coding-skills-as-you-2', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:46:21', '2015-05-12 19:46:21', '', 185, 'http://localhost/acnew/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Enlighten-your-coding-skills-as-you-2.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(190, 1, '2015-05-12 19:46:23', '2015-05-12 19:46:23', '<h2>If you don''t use it, you lose it</h2>\r\nWe all know that becoming a solid software developer is not something that happens in a day.\r\n\r\nHowever, one should not stop learning when he knows enough coding to land a good job. Coding is an exercise like running, swimming, or playing a musical instrument: if you don''t practice enough, you will get rusty.\r\n\r\nIt''s worth noting there are several categories of coding problems which we do not usually exercise in our everyday jobs, like algorithms to deal with sorting, searching, compressing, cryptography, artificial intelligence, machine learning, combinatorics, or geometry...\r\n\r\nNot only that, but as time goes by, other paradigms come forth in order to solve problems in a faster and more clever way, like Functional Programming and Reactive Programming.\r\n<h2>Leveling up</h2>\r\nThat said, there is just one way to keep sharp on software development: <strong>practicing</strong>. Now tell me: do you revel in leveling up while playing videogames, solving a Rubik''s cube, or even doing crosswords?\r\n\r\nSo why not taking coding challenges as well?\r\n\r\nI believe that every self-respecting software developer should put aside some weekly time to solve coding challenges. I personally strive for doing at least one short challenge per day. Over time, it starts to get entertaining, fun, and even addictive!\r\n\r\nThere are quite a few good websites that can provide great coding challenges to play with, leveling from 101 to top-notch. The beauty of it is that you will learn a lot when you compare your solution with others from the community. I believe that this way I will turn out to be a better developer on the long run. Besides, they end up being great puzzles to play with!\r\n<h2></h2>\r\nThese are short code challenge websites:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.codewars.com/">http://www.codewars.com/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.hackerrank.com/">http://www.hackerrank.com/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.hackerearth.com/">http://www.hackerearth.com/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf you would rather taking longer and more complex challenges (and sometimes get prizes for it):\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.topcoder.com/">http://www.topcoder.com/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://code.google.com/codejam">https://code.google.com/codejam</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.codechef.com/">http://www.codechef.com/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAnd if you only want to have fun, there are real videogames that you have to code in order to progress:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://codecombat.com/">http://codecombat.com/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.kuatostudios.com/games/hakitzu-elite/">http://www.kuatostudios.com/games/hakitzu-elite/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://play.elevatorsaga.com/">http://play.elevatorsaga.com/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nGive them a try and rejoice!', 'Enlighten your coding skills as you would play a videogame', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '185-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:46:23', '2015-05-12 19:46:23', '', 185, 'http://localhost/acnew/185-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(191, 1, '2015-05-12 19:46:41', '2015-05-12 19:46:41', '', 'Fresh-graduate', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'fresh-graduate', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:46:41', '2015-05-12 19:46:41', '', 186, 'http://localhost/acnew/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Fresh-graduate.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(192, 1, '2015-05-12 19:46:44', '2015-05-12 19:46:44', '<h2>The beginning</h2>\r\nThere I was. 24 years old, just got out of the University with my bachelor''s degree in Information Systems. Time to march out to face the competition and make a name for myself in the world. Some doors were opened but they would not lead far. I had to do something that would be worth my time and take advantage of everything I learned. But colleges nowadays are so far removed from what companies actually need! Even though they know how to teach people to think and make the best out of themselves.\r\n<h2>First steps</h2>\r\nSo what’s almost more valuable than your degree? Connections. A friend that was an Avenue Code Insider told me about a job opening, as I was working in mobile development at the time. "Send me your skills by email in English", he said. Some time passed by, and then I found myself at the Belo Horizonte''s office doing the interview. "Do you speak English?" they asked. I was confident about it, but, despite my language skills, I knew I was about to deal with my first interview totally in English. The lack of practice did not diminish my thinking skills, and, in the end, I was being seen as a potential developer. "You got skills, but you still don''t have the requirements we would like you to have. For these people, we offer the Trainee Program."\r\n<h2>Proving ground</h2>\r\nYes, I got in. And I would have three months to prove my value as a fast learner and competent developer. I aimed to improve every UI skill: HTML, CSS, Javascript, version control, modern frameworks, best practices, everything one may find as a trending topic in front-end conferences. I talked to people about where should I start, went to online teaching websites, found instructive videos, and made myself aware.\r\n\r\nSocially, Avenue Code''s flat hierarchy helped by giving me more space to ask questions, but the major difference was really the employees’ proactive way of helping, despite their deadlines and projects. On the other hand, the freedom of learning at my own pace, and not knowing where to apply that, put me in a gray area.\r\n<h2>Getting my hands dirty</h2>\r\nIn the mean time, I was put on an internal project. It helped me build chemistry with my co-workers and also build my knowledge. It was an awesome experience for me, as I could focus on putting my recent learnings into practice. Also, I could see how a project worked from the inside and contribute to challenges I could come across only in theory while at the university.\r\n\r\nAs part of the Trainee process, I had to pick one topic and do a talk. I chose Ember.js and the talk is <a href="http://youtu.be/mmMxaCRz9Mg">here</a>. It was a major achievement for me: it was great to see all the people attending my talk because I had something new to share, despite being a newcomer. After three months of dedication, I was hired. I am currently working on a client and I feel that I''ve been completely integrated into the Avenue Code team. There is much to be achieved and I appreciate the opportunity to grow as a UI Developer.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'From Trainee to UI Developer', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '186-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:46:44', '2015-05-12 19:46:44', '', 186, 'http://localhost/acnew/186-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(193, 1, '2015-05-12 19:47:06', '2015-05-12 19:47:06', '', 'Case-Study-graphic-4', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'case-study-graphic-4', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:47:06', '2015-05-12 19:47:06', '', 187, 'http://localhost/acnew/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Case-Study-graphic-4.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
