(240, 1, '2015-05-12 20:36:01', '2015-05-12 20:36:01', '<p style="text-align: center;">I was born in Scotland and spent three weeks there this Summer with my wife to celebrate our wedding anniversary. We were married immediately after we graduated from Edinburgh University and honeymooned in Scotland. As we were poor as church mice we had no money for a honeymoon, so a friend’s parents friend gave us a week in a cottage on a large estate in a Scottish countryside. The cottage was fully stocked and they were so nice it was a magical time.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Unfortunately over the years we lost track of our friend and were not sure where we had honeymooned. Our objective was to go to Scotland and find the cottage, celebrate with friends and do some sightseeing. Scotland is part of the United Kingdom (made up of Scotland, England, Wales and Northern Ireland). It is as far North as Juneau Alaska!! Fortunately the Gulf Stream keeps it warmer…… but that means that it rains a lot, in fact it rained 20 days out of 22 days that we were there.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00575.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-282" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00575-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00575" width="800" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">We did find the cottage, on the Ardverikie estate near Loch Laggan, here is a picture. The rest of the time we met friends and went sight seeing.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00592.jpeg"><img class="wp-image-283" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00592-168x300.jpeg" alt="DSC00592" width="300" height="533" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Scotland is famous for: <strong>Whisky</strong>, so we bought some really nice whisky, this was at the Dalwhinnie distillery, 900 dollars worth. It better taste REALLY good.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00628.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-284" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00628-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00628" width="800" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Golf</strong>, so I played in some of the best courses in the world, including Castle Stuart, where they play the Scottish open,</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00800.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-285" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00800-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00800" width="800" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Food</strong>, we had some truly special seafood, including this enormous lobster. This is my wife Evelyn and daughter Stephanie.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/haggis.jpg"><img class="wp-image-286" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/haggis.jpg" alt="haggis" width="600" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">and <strong>haggis</strong> of course, made from all the parts of a sheep that you would not normally eat.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00515.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-287" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00515-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00515" width="800" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">and we bought a new house (not):-)</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">If you are planning to go to Scotland, remember that it can be cold, and it might rain every day, but the scenery is stunning.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00509.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-288" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00509-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00509" width="800" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00512.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-290" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00512-1024x545.jpeg" alt="DSC00512" width="800" height="426" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00744.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-292" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00744-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00744" width="800" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00808.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-293" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00808-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00808" width="800" height="450" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00776.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-298" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00776-1024x576.jpeg" alt="DSC00776" width="800" height="451" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/IMG_0729.jpeg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-299" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/IMG_0729-1024x768.jpeg" alt="IMG_0729" width="800" height="600" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">...and the people are very friendly.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00633.jpeg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-301" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/DSC00633-576x1024.jpeg" alt="DSC00633" width="576" height="1024" /></a>\r\nContact me if you are thinking about going to Scotland.</p>', 'Revisiting the Scottish Countryside', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '232-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 20:36:01', '2015-05-12 20:36:01', '', 232, 'http://localhost/acnew/232-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(241, 1, '2015-05-12 20:36:32', '2015-05-12 20:36:32', '', 'infographic_v2', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'infographic_v2', '', '', '2015-05-12 20:36:32', '2015-05-12 20:36:32', '', 233, 'http://localhost/acnew/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/infographic_v2.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(242, 1, '2015-05-12 20:36:35', '2015-05-12 20:36:35', 'Many enterprise software developers still wonder why everyone is so concerned with client-side applications, HTML 5, Javascript, and front-end related "stuff." Such skills are very notable on job postings nowadays, even for enterprise development based on Java, .NET, and Rails (which are server-side technologies). A developer might ask: Why does nobody seem to care anymore that I have a Java architect certification if I don''t know about RequireJS, AngularJS or <em>whatever</em>JS (front-end development tools)?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe truth is that pretty much every enterprise software developer from the last decade should expect an evolution boom on the server-side development instead of the client-side. Just look at how Java, .NET, and Rails have developed across MVC frameworks, web services, cloud connectivity, security, multi-threading, and persistence. As if this wasn''t enough, server-side development trends towards SOA, ESB, EAI and clusterization are very notable as well. So what is going on?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAbout a decade ago, web applications started overtaking desktop applications (usually developed in Java Swing or VB.NET) in order to improve compatibility with the user''s computers. By adopting HTML for the user interface (UI), we no longer need to worry about the user''s operational system, as long as the user can access a web browser. This way, our software can even support mobile devices!￼\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow, let''s get back to the server-side enterprise development. While it is continuously evolving, it is still part of a web application bound to the same known limitations for the web such as request, response, session, cookies, and so on.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBuddy, you gotta trust me when I say the end user doesn''t care that the server-side is perfectly engineered when the client-side is sluggish—all that the user sees is the web application as a whole concept. This means that the user experience (UX) must be prioritized as well, otherwise this user might switch to another vendor with a more effective UI.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/infographic_v2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-200" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/infographic_v2-1024x819.jpg" alt="infographic_v2" width="796" height="637" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWith the web browser as the ultimate UI software, we need to overcome its limitations and provide the best possible UX in order to attract more users. And all they want are fully featured applications that are fast, responsive, and stable—as desktop applications have been in the past.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis, buddy, is what this fuss is all about—providing the desktop experience to the web user. This is the ultimate goal of every web application. This is the key to win the market.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAll in all, it comes down to a few line items:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>1. Reducing the page load time.</strong> This can be achieved with a few optimization techniques such as compiling all JS files and CSS files to a single JS file and CSS file, minifying those files, compressing the response using gzip, and adopting a CDN (Content Distribution Network) to deliver such files from a server closer to the end user. All of this can be automatized using a task runner such as Grunt or Gulp.js.\r\n<strong>2. Reducing the response time from seconds to milliseconds.</strong> This can be achieved by using more AJAX to fetch only the data and leave the rendering to the browser. For this rendering we have Javascript template engines such as Mustache, Handlebars.js, dust.js, or Jade.\r\n<strong>3. Improving the navigation experience.</strong> This can be achieved by getting rid of page reloads, so the user would see the site as a SPA (Single-Page Application). For that we have Javascript MV* frameworks such as Backbone.js, AngularJS, Ember.js, or Knockout.\r\n<strong>4. Reducing the Javascript processing time.</strong> This can be achieved by adopting an asynchronous Javascript module loader such as RequireJS or YepNope. Favoring native browser features instead of depending on plugins such as Flash to render animations, audio, and video. This can now be achieved with HTML 5, CSS 3, SVG, and OpenGL.\r\n<strong>5. Adopting reusable components to improve semantics and save in downloaded content.</strong> A new universe of Web Components is coming out soon, and currently can be achieved with libraries such as Polymer and X-Tag.\r\n<strong>6. There is much more about optimizing web pages, so do your own research about other techniques available.</strong> Make sure you look at HTTP2 &amp; SPDY, WebSockets for transmitting binary data, localStorage, and offline mode.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMy final advice is that every type of software developer needs to learn more about all these new libraries and stay tuned to the front-end technologies. You won''t regret it—and nor will your resume!', 'What is all the fuss about with front-end development?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '233-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 20:36:35', '2015-05-12 20:36:35', '', 233, 'http://localhost/acnew/233-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(243, 1, '2014-07-02 21:37:57', '2014-07-02 21:37:57', 'William Hom, a project manager and iteration manager, took a two-week vacation with his daughter in Cusco, Peru. Are you picturing a happy dad and his little daughter wandering around colorful, exciting Spanish-influenced buildings and temples, and some beautiful archaeological sites?\r\n\r\nIt turns out that William didn’t have quite those exotic and extravagant moments with his daughter. His daughter didn’t even have a break from school! Rather, William decided to volunteer with a charitable organization called IVHQ (International Volunteer Headquarters) in Cusco, Peru. Let’s hear more about his extraordinary vacation.<strong>\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/pic1.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-161" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/pic1-199x300.png" alt="Cusco" width="199" height="300" /></a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>AC:</strong> Why did you decide to go to the trip?  <strong>\r\n</strong><strong>WH:</strong> I wanted to take an unconventional vacation, and to involve my 15 year old daughter in working in developing countries in a volunteering capacity such as in an orphanage or pre-school setting.\r\n\r\n<strong>AC: </strong>What was daily schedule like?  <strong>\r\n</strong><strong>WH:</strong> For the mornings from 8:30 a.m. to 12:30 p.m., we spent the time working at a pre-school (ages 4 and 5) as a teacher''s aide for about 45 minutes by bus ride outside of Cusco, and in the afternoon from 2:00 P.M. to 4:00 p.m., we took basic Spanish classes provided by the organization.\r\n\r\n<strong>AC: </strong>What were the most memorable moments?  <strong>\r\n</strong><strong>WH: </strong>Donating 46 pairs of shoes that we brought with us through my daughter’s shoe drive to an all girls orphanage.  We lugged 2 large duffel bags to Peru in all different sizes.  Most of the girls were extremely grateful about the shoes and prepared a prayer dedicated to us.\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong><strong>AC: </strong>What challenges did you encounter during the trip?  <strong>\r\n</strong><strong>WH: </strong>The basic necessities we take for granted were minimal.  For example, we stayed with a host family during our volunteering activities and found that during their winter, we didn''t have a heater in our rooms.  The shower had little hot water.  Toilet paper was not to be flushed down the toilet.  And since both my daughter and I did not speak Spanish, we had to overcome many challenges to communicate.\r\n\r\n<strong>AC: </strong>What lessons/insights/realization did you gain from the trip?  <strong>\r\n</strong><strong>WH: </strong>We take for granted how fortunate we are in this country, even in down times.  Our bad days are their good days.  We pay taxes for a reason and we realize the benefits of a great infrastructure.  One of the things I did notice was how happy the children were.  They were very content with their lives.  Their families are very supportive and are close knit.  My daughter was probably the most to benefit from this trip and I was fortunate to provide her this opportunity to see how other people live, work, and play.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/pic2.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-162" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/pic2-300x199.png" alt="pic2" width="300" height="199" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>AC:</strong> Would you go again if you have a chance?  <strong>\r\n</strong><strong>WH:</strong> My daughter is asking when we can go again.  She was extremely sad when we left, and misses the kids.\r\n\r\n<strong>AC:</strong> If somebody asks you, “What is Avenue Code?,” how would you explain it to him/her in one sentence? <strong>\r\n</strong><strong>WH:</strong> Avenue Code is a company fostering and evangelizing the benefits of Agile development and methodology in order to help companies offer their products to the marketplace at a faster rate and realize business value quicker.\r\n\r\nThough William and his daughter might not have had a physically comforting and entertaining vacation, they indeed made unforgettable memories in Cusco. Working together side by side with one  another for others, they bonded on a deeper level and they gained a greater appreciation of what they have.\r\n\r\nAvenue Code is proud to have William as part of the team. If you have an extraordinary experience that you’d like to share with us, please contact Summer Kim at <a href="mailto:skim@avenuecode.com">skim@avenuecode.com</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Extraordinary Vacation in Cusco, Peru', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'extraordinary-vacation-in-cusco-peru', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:18:49', '2015-05-18 17:18:49', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=243', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(244, 1, '2014-06-24 20:57:10', '2014-06-24 20:57:10', '<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/cover1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-167" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/cover1-300x214.jpg" alt="How do you spell Kanban?" width="300" height="214" /></a>\r\n\r\nThis week has been one for the patience skill.  As a veteran Agilist and now coach/trainer  for 2 years, I often come across folks that have very little knowledge regarding the Agile framework items.  This past week presented yet another one of those times. I have a new Mentee as of this week and she is starting from ground zero.  At the end of this month, I will have been on this engagement for 10 months and after 6 years, I still have to remind myself that Agile has funny words.  I forget that mainstream Agile has adopted terms from Japan. I forget that mainstream Agile has adopted terms from Lean. I forget that mainstream Agile has adopted sports terms.  They all just seems like every day words to me.  Having said that, just the other day, I believe it was Tuesday, I looked over at my Mentee as said, "For this project we are going to be doing more Kanban style than Scrum. Perhaps you can look up some articles online so you can see the differences."  She turned to me and said, "How do you spell Kanban?"', 'How do you spell Kanban?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-do-you-spell-kanban', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:20:01', '2015-05-18 17:20:01', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=244', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(245, 1, '2014-06-05 21:36:17', '2014-06-05 21:36:17', 'Friday was an epic day for me and my client.  My original assignment of designing and developing a persistent agile team is now delivered!\r\n\r\nBack in November I originally came on board to do this very task.  I got side tracked into delivery a different very high profile project instead for 8 months. Upon the delivery of that project, I am back to my original assignment.  Here’s how it’s different than most agile teams here.\r\nThis team supports an escalated level of production support. A story can come through the fast lane and need to be dealt with immediately.  So, previously determined work would need to be put back in the backlog… it’s more kanban then scrum since the work commitment can be changed during the sprint. The team size is set and dedicated; no difference here.  The story is done when it’s done.\r\n\r\nIn theory this approach is easy but in practice this takes a lot of discipline.  Since my client is a large enterprise with many project teams active, it’s hard to keep people from for lack of better work, “interfering”.  If you want to know more, contact Avenue Code about this one…\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'An Epic Day...', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'an-epic-day', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:23:15', '2015-05-18 17:23:15', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=245', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(246, 1, '2014-05-29 21:35:30', '2014-05-29 21:35:30', 'Lean Principles (come from Toyota Production System / Kanban - meaning "billboard") focus on elimination of waste (just in time production, replenishment triggered by demand), no iterations, switch tasking is minimized by setting work limits. Production is driven directly by customer demand -- close interaction with customers. Anything that does not generate immediate customer value is not being worked on. The goal is to improve by amplifying learning, eliminate constrains, empower the team while making decisions as late as possible.\r\n\r\nAgile is a framework for various methodologies: scrum, xp, pair. The Agile Manifesto (2001) was drafted by 17 software developers who got together at a Utah ski resort and agreed on the governing principles.\r\n\r\nIt is important to understand that Agile is a style of working, a mentality. <strong>We are not doing agile, but rather we are being agile.</strong>\r\n\r\nThe focus is on iterative, time boxed activity cycles and planning. No task limits are stated but rather team capacity measurements dictate the burn rate and productivity potential. Agile values people over process or tools and promotes co-location (business/customer and developers sit together), self organized teams, trusting the team, continuous integration, sustainability and adaptability (response to change) to build discipline. Team roles are also an important component of this practice. All this creates a cultural transition.\r\n\r\nLean Startup Concept is Eric Ries'' philosophy that focuses on creating a minimum viable product (unfinished product). It has nothing to do with funding or raising capital! To achieve this startups must eliminate waste (no lengthy business plans but rather a prototype or pitch) and focus on customer value using key performance indicators and a continuous deployment process."\r\n\r\nHow have these methodologies helped  your projects and organizations?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBy: Valerie Muravitsky\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Lean and Agile', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'lean-and-agile', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:23:28', '2015-05-18 17:23:28', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=246', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(247, 1, '2015-05-12 20:48:54', '2015-05-12 20:48:54', '', 'pic1', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'pic1', '', '', '2015-05-12 20:48:54', '2015-05-12 20:48:54', '', 243, 'http://localhost/acnew/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/pic1.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
